Class StringValue

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.salesforce.omakase.ast.AbstractSyntax

          • com.salesforce.omakase.ast.declaration.StringValue
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Groupable<PropertyValue,PropertyValueMember>, PropertyValueMember, Term, Syntax, Broadcastable, Writable

    public final class StringValue
extends AbstractTerm
    A string value, e.g., "Times New Roman".

    Note that the reason a setter for quotation mode doesn't exist is that it must not be set independent of the content (which could contain incompatible), so use content(QuotationMode, String) (and verify the content and quotation mode are compatible) instead.

    See Also:
    StringValueParser

    • Constructor Detail

      • StringValue

        public StringValue(int line,
                   int column,
                   QuotationMode mode,
                   String content)
        Constructs a new StringValue instance.

        The QuotationMode is required so that we can preserve the original quotes used in the source. Performance-wise, there is no reason to change it from the original, and also it keeps us from having to mess around with escaping.

        * If dynamically creating a new instance then use StringValue(QuotationMode, String) instead.

        Parameters:
        line - The line number.
        column - The column number.
        mode - The QuotationMode to use when printing out the value.
        content - The content of the string.

      • write

        public void write(StyleWriter writer,
                  StyleAppendable appendable)
           throws IOException
        Description copied from interface: Writable
        Outputs this Writable's string representation.

        Important notes for implementation:

        Do not use the StyleWriter in an attempt to write direct content (Strings, chars, etc...). Use the StyleAppendable.

        The StyleWriter should be used to make decisions based on writer settings (e.g., compressed vs. verbose output mode), as well as for writing inner or child Writables. Do not call the this method method directly on inner or child Writables! That would bypass any overrides that are set on the StyleWriter. Use StyleWriter.writeInner(Writable, StyleAppendable) instead.

        Parameters:
        writer - Writer to use for output settings and for writing inner Writables.
        appendable - Append direct content to this StyleAppendable.
        Throws:
        IOException - If an I/O error occurs.
